'''Sakatoke Shrine''' (自玉手祭来酒解神社, たまでよりまつりきたるさかとけじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Kyoto Prefecture|ja|京都府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Prefecture|qq=}}, {{ill|Otokun District|ja|乙訓郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otokun District|qq=}}, {{ill|Ōyamazaki Town|ja|大山崎町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazaki Town|qq=}}. Its common name is '''Sakatoke Shrine''' (酒解神社, さかとけじんじゃ, さかときじんじゃ). It is situated near the summit of {{ill|Tennozan|ja|天王山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tennozan|qq=}}. It is listed as a {{ill|Shikinai Shrine|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|lt=Meishindai|lt_ja=名神大|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinai Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}}, and in the old {{ill|Modern Shrine Ranking system|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern Shrine Ranking system|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}} it was designated as a Gōsha.

==祭神==
It enshrines {{ill|Ōyamatsumi|ja|大山祇神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|qq=}} as its main deity and {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|スサノオ|lt=Susanoo|lt_ja=素盞嗚尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}} as its secondary deity.

==歴史==
The origins of its founding are unclear; however, a ridge plaque dating to the first year of the {{ill|Yōrō|ja|養老|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yōrō|qq=}} era ({{ill|717 AD|ja|717th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/717 AD|qq=}}) indicates that it was established during the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara period|qq=}}. It was formerly known as Yamazaki no Mori (山埼杜) and was enshrined at the site of the present {{ill|Rikyū Hachiman Shrine|ja|離宮八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rikyū Hachiman Shrine|qq=}}. In the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, the {{ill|Engi Shiki Shinmei-chō|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engi Shiki Shinmei-chō|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}} recorded the name as “Yamashiro Province, Otokun District, Sakatoke Shrine, formerly Yamazaki no Mori,” listing it among the state-sponsored {{ill|Meishindai Shrine|ja|名神大社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meishindai Shrine|qq=}} and noting that offerings for the monthly and New Rice Festival were entrusted to it.

Subsequently, the enshrinement at Sakatoke Shrine lapsed, and its whereabouts were unknown until the Meiji period. The present Sakatoke Shrine was formerly the Yamazaki Tenno Shrine, which enshrined the deity Tenno Hachijōjin ({{ill|Gyūto Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyūto Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|qq=}}) that had been venerated near the summit of Tennozan since medieval times. Although Tennozan was originally called Yamazaki-yama, it came to be known as Tennozan in association with this shrine. In June of the 10th year of the {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}}, the Yamazaki Tenno Shrine was recognized as a Shikinai Shrine and renamed Sakatoke Shrine. The current main deity, Ōyamatsumi, was designated at that time.

The shrine’s mikoshi storehouse has been designated as an important cultural property by the nation.

